assic and very important game to chess history went} 20. f4 $2 {an aggressive attempt that was convingly refuted with active play:} Bd2 $1 21. Qc4 Rd4 22. Qb3 ( 23. Ne6 $2 {fails due to} Qf7 $1 $19  ) exf4 23. gxf4 Qe7 $1 24. Nd3 Be6 $17 {Alekhine,A-Euwe,M World-ch15 Euwe-Alekhine +9-8=13 1935 (21) 0-1 White's position is a tragedy: his structure is totally compromised, his pieces badly coordinated and Black's pieces are very active. This was another masterpiece by Dr. Euwe in his historical first match against Alekhine.}  ) ( 20. Nd3 Bxa5 21. Qc5 Bb6 22. Qxe5+ Qxe5 23. Nxe5 Bd4 24. Nd3 O-O $15  ) Rd4 20. Qc1 {White manages to keep the a5-pawn tactically defended, but in this case we can evaluate the position as a perfectly decent one for us.} Qe7 21. Nd3 Bd6 22. Qc3 Be6 $11 {Farago,I (2363) -Hess,C (2214) Bad Woerishofen opA 35th 2019 (9.4) 1/2-1/2 With an equal game. The main point of 11...f6 is that Black doesn't compromise his pawn structure, which happens to be the case in the most critical lines which will be analysed in the next chapters. If White plays carelessly, we can often easily get the better position!}  *

